                class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-1008140 -fit">
        </noscript>
        </span>
        <p id="caption-attachment-1008140" class="wp-caption-text">A stuffed doll of Pepe the Frog sits at the main entrance of the Hong Kong Polytechnic University campus in Hong Kong on Nov. 23, 2019. <span class="attribution">Anthony Kwan/Getty Images</span> <!-- caption placeholder --></p></div>
<h4>3. <a href="https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/06/01/canada-may-host-the-worlds-first-incel-show-trial/">Canada May Host the World’s First Incel Show Trial</a></h4>
<p>A 17-year-old who allegedly killed a woman in Toronto due to his own sexual frustrations will be charged with terrorism. Simon Cottee asks whether men who identify with the online “incel” community should be treated as terrorists.</p>
<hr class="thick-horizontal-rule" />
<div id="attachment_1008467" class="wp-caption alignnone none text_width">            <span
                style="padding-bottom:66.625%;
        "
                class="image-attachment -ratioscale">
        <img
            data-srcset="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg 4302w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=150,100 150w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=550,367 550w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=768,512 768w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=1536,1024 1536w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=2048,1365 2048w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=400,267 400w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=401,267 401w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=800,533 800w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=1920,1280 1920w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=275,183 275w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=325,217 325w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?resize=600,400 600w"
            data-src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?w=800"
            alt="U.S. President Donald Trump leaves the White House to go to St. John&#039;s Church in Washington on June 1."
            class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-1008467 -fit -lazy">
        <noscript>
            <img
                src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1216826728.jpg?w=800"
                alt="U.S. President Donald Trump leaves the White House to go to St. John&#039;s Church in Washington on June 1."
                class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-1008467 -fit">
        </noscript>
        </span>
        <p id="caption-attachment-1008467" class="wp-caption-text">U.S. President Donald Trump leaves the White House to go to St. John&#8217;s Church in Washington on June 1. <span class="attribution">BRENDAN SMIALOWSKI/AFP via Getty Images</span> <!-- caption placeholder --></p></div>
<h4>4. <a href="https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/06/03/trump-military-george-floyd-protests/">A Moment of National Shame and Peril—and Hope</a></h4>
<p>The Trump administration’s response to protests in Washington could mark the country’s slide into illiberalism, John Allen writes.</p>
<hr class="thick-horizontal-rule" />
<div id="attachment_1008372" class="wp-caption alignnone none text_width">            <span
                style="padding-bottom:66.625%;
        "
                class="image-attachment -ratioscale">
        <img
            data-srcset="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg 4000w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=150,100 150w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=550,367 550w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=768,512 768w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=1536,1024 1536w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=2048,1366 2048w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=400,267 400w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=401,267 401w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=800,533 800w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=1920,1280 1920w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=275,183 275w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=325,217 325w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?resize=600,400 600w"
            data-src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?w=800"
            alt="Employees eating lunch at a Dongfeng Honda auto plant in Wuhan, China, shortly after returning to work, on March 23."
            class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-1008372 -fit -lazy">
        <noscript>
            <img
                src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/GettyImages-1208074563.jpg?w=800"
                alt="Employees eating lunch at a Dongfeng Honda auto plant in Wuhan, China, shortly after returning to work, on March 23."
                class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-1008372 -fit">
        </noscript>
        </span>
        <p id="caption-attachment-1008372" class="wp-caption-text">Employees eat lunch at a Dongfeng Honda auto plant in Wuhan, China, shortly after returning to work, on March 23. <span class="attribution">STR/AFP via Getty Images</span> <!-- caption placeholder --></p></div>
<h4>5. <a href="https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/06/02/as-economies-reopen-its-the-law-of-the-jungle-for-workers/">As Economies Reopen, It’s the Law of the Jungle for Workers</a></h4>
<p>As communities and businesses around the world decide on the next tentative steps to loosen lockdowns and return to business, exposure to a possible second wave of coronavirus infections is the main worry, Michael Moran writes.</p>
